:R-HSA-5690714  a           owl:NamedIndividual , obo:GO_0008150 ;
        rdfs:comment        "BCR activation is highly regulated and coreceptors like CD22 (SIGLEC2) set a signalling threshold to prevent aberrant immune response and autoimmune disease (Cyster et al. 1997, Han et al. 2005). CD22 is a glycoprotein found on the surface of B cells during restricted stages of development. CD22 is a member of the receptors of the sialic acid-binding Ig-like lectin (Siglec) family which binds specifically to the terminal sequence N-acetylneuraminic acid alpha(2-6) galactose (NeuAc-alpha(2-6)-Gal) present on many B-cell glycoproteins (Powell et al. 1993, Sgroi et al. 1993). CD22 has seven immunoglobulin (Ig)-like extracellular domains and a cytoplasmic tail containing six tyrosines, three of which belong to the inhibitory immunoreceptor tyrosine-based inhibition motifs (ITIMs) sequences. Upon BCR cross-linking CD22 is rapidly tyrosine phosphorylated by the tyrosine kinase Lyn, thereby recruiting and activating tyrosine phosphatase, SHP-1 and inhibiting calcium signalling." ;
        rdfs:label          "CD22 mediated BCR regulation" ;
        dc:contributor      "GOC:reactome_curators" , "Edited: Garapati, Phani Vijay, 2015-04-30" , "Authored: Garapati, Phani Vijay, 2015-04-30" , "Reviewed: Paulson, James C, 2015-11-09" ;
        dc:date             "2026-06-29" ;
        pav:providedBy      "https://reactome.org" ;
        oboInOwl:hasDbXref  "R-HSA-5690714" ;
        skos:narrower       <http://model.geneontology.org/R-HSA-983705/R-HSA-983705> ;
        skos:note           "org.biopax.paxtools.model.level3.Pathway" .

